{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e0ee9925-f4c5-425b-8d2d-85c3448f44cb","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile, collected directly inside the pod:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Install the tool (if not already in the image)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can copy out and analyze:\n\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\nOpen it in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **Speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- Use `--duration` or press `Enter` to stop — avoid overly large traces.\n- If you can't install tools in the pod, use a **sidecar** or **ephemeral debug container** (`kubectl debug`).\n- For production, `dotnet-monitor` is a lighter-weight alternative that exposes trace collection via an HTTP API without exec'ing in.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3df3111f-1144-4893-b0e4-bd7eeb59eabe","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":350},"id":"e5ccb41a-06b7-4db8-95ee-9dfeb7ef3218","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:48:58.498Z","parentId":"40ae7d3e-d938-4434-bbfa-607f2ea8008c"}
